[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Professor Gallagher and Mr 
[normal]Holtham
[normal], thank you very much indeed for coming along here this morning. I am David Davies, Chair of the Welsh Affairs Select Committee
[normal]. W
[normal]e are here to scrutinise the new Government of Wales Bill, as you probably know. 
[normal]If I may, I will
[normal] turn
[normal] to Mark Williams to start with.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Williams:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you very much
[normal] and thank you, gentlemen; i
[normal]t is good to see you here. My questions relate to improving financial accountability. Silk was very clear in his report when he said 
[normal]that “
[normal]the current funding arrangements for the Welsh Government do not meet the re
[normal]quirements of a mature democracy”.
[normal] In the foreword to the draft Bill
[normal],
[normal] the Secretary of State for 
[normal]Wales
[normal] has said that 
[normal]“
[normal]These changes will give 
[normal]Wales
[normal] more fiscal autonomy, and will make the Assembly and the Welsh Government more accountable to
[normal]” the
[normal] people 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]Wales
[normal].
[normal] Do you accept that improving financial accountability is the key argument for devolving taxes?
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: 
[normal]In general, yes, I think that that is right. Gerry will speak for himself, but I suspect he may agree with me
[normal] here.
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]hat is very striking about the devolved bodies across the 
[normal]UK
[normal], including in 
[normal]Wales
[normal], is that they were
[normal] set up from former Government D
[normal]epartments whose job was to spend rather than to raise money, but once they become Governments
[normal],
[normal] they ought to have the power to raise money as well as spend it. Raising it gives them the option of having some say over how much they spend
[normal],
[normal] and setting a tax rate makes them fiscally accountable to their voters.
[normal]Gerald [bold]Holtham[bold]: Yes, indeed;
[normal] I entirely agree. I think one should note in the Welsh case how very small a step this is. The three small taxes under consideration might have a revenue yield of £200 million a year, which, against a budget of £15 billion, verges on insignificant. It is a 
[normal]good gesture, but it is not much more than a gesture. Of course, if the referendum is held and income tax is partly devolved, that will be somewhat more significant.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Williams:[bold] 
[normal]Notwithstanding what you 
[normal]have 
[normal]said about the scale of the changes and the figures you mentioned, what hard evidence is out there and available to us to show that fiscal devolution does indeed promote greater accountability? I do not know what indicators we should be looking for
[normal]—
[normal]perhaps you have 
[normal]looked at
[normal] that in your respective work
[normal]—but what is the
[normal] hard evidence that this does improve the
[normal] situation?
[normal]Gerald [bold]Holtham[bold]: 
[normal]Internationally
[normal],
[normal] there is some evidence that fiscal devolution leads to
[normal] a flattening of tax schedules 
[normal]because tax competition is more effective at the top end. People on basic rate tax do not move because the basic rate changes. If you think about it, putting a penny on the basic rate cannot cost anybody more than £300 or £400
[normal] a year
[normal], which does not pay for a removal van
[normal];
[normal] so nobody is going anywhere. But if you start taxing millionaires, they can move around. 
[normal]T
[normal]he presence of tax devolution means that there is some tax competition among authorities
[normal],
[normal] and that does tend to flatten tax schedules. I do not know whether you would count that as 
[normal]a 
[normal]responsibility
[normal],
[normal] but it shows 
[normal]that 
[normal]people are responsive to the opportunities that tax devolution affords them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Williams:[bold] 
[normal]As a very general
[normal],
[normal] almost kick
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]off question
[normal]—
[normal]my colleagues are going to go into some of these issues in more depth
[normal]—
[normal]what are the advantages and disadvantages associated with the devolving of income and land taxes?
[normal]Gerald [bold]Holtham[bold]: 
[normal]Land taxes are a fairly obvious thing to devolve
[normal],
[normal] and that is probably why local authority taxation in the UK has always been based on some form of property tax
[normal]—
[normal]the old rates and now council tax
[normal]—
[normal]because the tax base is n
[normal]ot mobile. I
[normal]t is easy to identify and 
[normal]it is a tax that is 
[normal]hard to evade
[normal]; it is 
[normal]a rooted tax base. 
[normal]I
[normal]f you are looking to extend the tax base of authorities that do not have an adequate tax base, looking for more taxes related to land does make sense, I think. 
[normal]The point about income tax is that it is a tax 
[normal]that
[normal] is very broadly paid and therefore it affects a large proportion of the electorate. 
[normal]As such, i
[normal]t increases the visibility of the tax policies of the devolved authority and, as such, it is a good tax from an accountability point of view. Unlike houses, people can move about, so there are consequences in terms of tax competition, as I have said, but in terms of being a broad
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based
[normal] and highly visible tax, and therefore serving accountability, it is a good one.
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: 
[normal]I would add two things
[normal] to that
[normal]. I agree with Gerry that, for decentralisation, immobile tax bases are the best
[normal],
[normal] and therefore property, being immobile, is very good. People are less mobile than some other potential tax bases
[normal]—
[normal]for example, corporate profits, which can be moved around. 
[normal]If you look at the taxes that are available for devolution,
[normal] there are only three big taxes. T
[normal]here is VAT, which cannot be decentralised under European law; 
[normal]there is 
[normal]national insurance, which is like income tax, but, in my view, for other reasons should not be decentralised; and there is income tax. As Gerry says, income tax is spread across the population
[normal]—
[normal]a lot of people pay it
[normal]—and it is also very perceptible;
[normal] people notice it. If you ask someone about tax 
[normal]rates, most often they would begin by talking about income tax rates. So it is a good tax for devolution because it can be decentralised and it is noticeable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Nia[bold] Griffith:[bold] 
[normal]I would like to take you up on that issue of 
[normal]“
[normal]noticeable
[normal]”
[normal], if I may. 
[normal]W
[normal]hen you are talking about the other 
[normal]taxes—the stamp duty, the land
[normal]fill and an
[normal] adjustment to the block grant—they
[normal] may not have much of an impact on people in the same way that a council tax bill comin
[normal]g through the door will or they see
[normal] 
[normal]in 
[normal]the newspaper 
[normal]it 
[normal]says they are going up 4%, or whatever. They see their bill
[normal],
[normal] and they think they are paying for all the council services
[normal],
[normal] when in fact there is 
[normal]actually
[normal] a block grant element there
[normal]. H
[normal]ow do you envisage it becoming visible for people? 
[normal]In w
[normal]hat way would that income tax power have to be used for people really to feel that they were having a say in whether the Welsh Government spent more or 
[normal]spent 
[normal]less
[normal]?
[normal] 
[normal]D
[normal]o you think it is realistic that the Welsh
[normal] Government would do something—i.e. raise it or lower it—
[normal]and how would that impact on people? Do you think it would actually happen?
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: There are two issues here: p
[normal]erceptibility
[normal], first of all. D
[normal]o people notice the tax at all? Quite often
[normal],
[normal] people would not notice an indirect tax like VAT or duty because they are not absolutely sure what proportion of what they are paying is for the product and what proportion is for the tax. At the other extreme, as you say, you have council tax where the bill comes through the door and you have to fork out the cash. That is extremely perceptible. 
[normal]Income tax is pretty perceptible for two reasons: one, because you see it in your pay slip every month and, two
[normal]—
[normal]and this is where we move into the question of accountability
[normal]—
[normal]because the Assembly would have to set a tax rate. It would have to make a tax decision. One of the interesting things about the way in which devolution has been funded in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] hitherto is that, for the most part, the devolved bodies, including the Welsh Assembly, do not have to make any tax decision but the money still flows. The Scottish comparison is interesting here because
[normal], although,
[normal] in principle, the Scottish Parliament had the power to vary income tax, it did not have 
[normal]to 
[normal]do anything
[normal]—and, f
[normal]unnily enough, it did not do anything. 
[normal]The advantage of an income tax power
[normal]—
[normal]or, to a lesser degree, the small taxes
[normal]—
[normal]is that the Assembly will have to take a tax decision and take a view as to whether it is better, to use Gladstone
[normal]’
[normal]s words, to allow the money to 
[normal]“
[normal]fructify
[normal]”
[normal] in the profits of the taxpayers or whether to spend money on services. 
[normal]T
[normal]hat is the decision they have to make. 
[normal]The issue you raise is an important one
[normal],
[normal] and that is that the total budget in comparison to the tax income is not that great
[normal],
[normal] and that 
[normal]does dilute the accountability—I agree—
[normal]but one has to have a look at the relative spend and the tax base that is available. There is no system all across the world in which a sub
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]national
[normal] Government gets all its money from the taxes it raises itself. They are all dependent on a mixture of some form of central subvention
[normal]—
[normal]a central grant, a share of taxes allocated or something of that sort
[normal]—
[normal]and taxes they raise themselves. 
[normal]In the Welsh case, we have to bear in mind 
[normal]that 
[normal]there is a substantial spending need and a relatively weak income tax base. Therefore, income tax is never going to be a huge proportion of the total Welsh spending. Nevertheless, it can be a significant one.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chair:[bold] I will just try
[normal] to bring 
[normal]in 
[normal]a couple more people 
[normal]briefly on this question.
[normal] Geraint Davies is next.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Geraint Davies:[bold] 
[normal]The case has been made that Wales is underfunded in terms of Barnett, certainly versus Scotland
[normal],
[normal] on the revenue side, and in terms of our share of capital
[normal] investment
[normal], as far as the UK is concerned, again we are underfunded. 
[normal]I
[normal]n terms of accountability, is it not the case that
[normal],
[normal] if the Gov
[normal]ernment are switching the focus o
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal]to borrowing, and indeed tax
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]raising
[normal] powers to pay for that borrowing for Wales, that the focus will go on to Wales and
[normal],
[normal] therefore
[normal],
[normal] there will be a reduction in the accountability of the UK Government
[normal],
[normal] who should be brought to account?
[normal]Gerald [bold]Holtham[bold]: 
[normal]There are a number of issues there. 
[normal]It is true, and w
[normal]ork we did back in 2010 suggested
[normal],
[normal] that
[normal],
[normal] if Wales were a region of England and you simply applied 
[normal]in Wales 
[normal]the needs
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based
[normal] formula
[normal]e used in England to distribute 
[normal]health spending and local government revenue support
[normal] around England, 
[normal]you would come to the conclusion that Wales is slightly un
[normal]derfunded by 2% or 3% 
[normal]relative to what it would get if it were an English region. 
[normal]I regard that as l
[normal]ess serious than the other fact
[normal] that
[normal],
[normal] with the 
[normal]Barnett formula
[normal], if unreformed, once public expenditure growth resumes
[normal]—I do not mean real growth but
[normal] just growth in nominal terms
[normal]—
[normal]the share of spending in Wales will fall relative to England. This is just a consequence of the 
[normal]way the formula is set up. Let’
[normal]s say in 
[normal]England
[normal] 
[normal]the Government decide
[normal] to spend £5 a hea
[normal]d more on any service you like. I
[normal]f that is a devolved service, 
[normal]Wales
[normal] would get £5 a head more. B
[normal]ut if you are starting from a situation where English expenditure is £100 a head, £5 on for £100 is 5%. If we are starting in 
[normal]Wales
[normal] where it is 110%
[normal]—as it would be, let’
[normal]s say, in the north
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]east of 
[normal]England
[normal] and other poorer areas
[normal]—
[normal]£5 on £110 is 4.5%, or something. So you are going to get a slow move to squeeze 
[normal]Wales
[normal] down to the average expenditure level in 
[normal]England
[normal], which does not happen in any of the areas of 
[normal]England
[normal]. If needs
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based
[normal] assessment says the north
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]east is poorer and should get more, it gets more; it is not squeezed to some average. 
[normal]The difficulty here is that the income tax devolution will necessarily
[normal]—
[normal]and
[normal],
[normal] in my opinion
[normal],
[normal] appropriately
[normal]—
[normal]increase the risks on the Welsh Government because you are replacing part of the block grant with your own income tax take, which will depend on the growth of the income tax base in your economy. If that grows more slowly than public expenditure in 
[normal]England
[normal], you are worse off as a result of this devolution. That is a risk. I think you have to take it because
[normal],
[normal] otherwise
[normal],
[normal] the Welsh Government 
[normal]are
[normal] currently in a position where
[normal],
[normal] if the economy goes to heck in a 
[normal]handbasket
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]they get
[normal] exactly the same money, or
[normal],
[normal] if 
[normal]they introduce
[normal] wonderful policies that result in the Welsh econo
[normal]my booming, they see no benefit and still get
[normal] the same money. 
[normal]Unfortunately, you cannot disentangle the necessary incentives and responsibility from that other risk that, for reasons you cannot control, your income tax base grows more slowly. 
[normal]I
[normal]t is a consequence of responsibility that you have to take that risk. But it would be very helpful if the other
[normal],
[normal] totally unnecessary risk implied by the 
[normal]Barnett formula
[normal] were removed. To me, the obvious thing to do here is to say, 
[normal]“
[normal]If you pass this income tax in a referendum, at the moment it is passed and you assume responsibilities for income tax
[normal],
[normal] we will put a floor under Barnett and cease the Barnett squeeze.
[normal]”
[normal] That would at least remove one ris
[normal]k—an unnecessary and unfair risk—
[normal]at the same time that you are imposing a necessary risk.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Geraint Davies:[bold] 
[normal]But surely you have described an incentive for the Welsh Government to spend more money on economic development when 
[normal]they are
[normal] not in charge of 
