[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hywel[bold] Williams:[bold] 
[normal]Briefly, 
[normal]going 
[normal]back to Professor Gallagher, you were talking about models from other parts of the world. When thi
[normal]s Committee visited the Basque c
[normal]ountry some years ago, we were told in some detail about their tax arrangements, 
[normal]which I have to confess I can’
[normal]t remember now. 
[normal]Are there particular lessons or i
[normal]s there a particular model there which would be an alternative?
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: 
[normal]No, I do 
[normal]not think there is. The Basque c
[normal]ountry is often cited as an example of so
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]called full fiscal autonomy. The headline description 
[normal]that
[normal] is given, which is not wholl
[normal]y accurate, is that the Basque c
[normal]ountry decides on and collects all the taxes and remits a so
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]called 
[normal]“
[normal]c
[normal]upo
[normal]”
[normal] to 
[normal]Madrid
[normal]. That is slightly misleading for three reasons. First,
[normal] it is not actually the Basque c
[normal]ountry itself but s
[normal]ubsidiary levels in the Basque c
[normal]ountry 
[normal]that
[normal] decide and collect taxes. Secondly, many of the taxes they do not actually decide but are simply responsible for collecting, such as value
[normal] 
[normal]added tax. Thirdly, one of the very major taxes they neither decide nor collect, which is social security contributions
[normal],
[normal] are decided and collected by the Government in 
[normal]Madrid
