[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Is there a model anywhere in the world that you think is a standard model, either in the B
[normal]asque c
[normal]ountry, 
[normal]Italy
[normal], 
[normal]Germany
[normal] or any of the devolved regions, for the percentage that a devolved region could normally be expected to raise by itself?
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: 
[normal]I do not think there is a model
[normal],
[normal] and one must remember here that there are two variables. The
[normal]y
[normal] are what proportion of spending is decentralised and what propor
[normal]tion of taxing is decentralised.
[normal] The proportion, therefore, of the devolved budget that is supported by tax depends on those two variables. 
[normal]I
[normal]f you have a big budget, as the Welsh Assembly does
[normal]—
[normal]it is responsible for pushing 40%, I think, off the top of my head, of public spending in Wales, 
[normal]and 
[normal]possibly more
[normal]—
[normal]and a small tax base, you therefore have a very small percentage of your budget. You could argue that
[normal],
[normal] if you wanted to gain greater, as it were, physical autonomy
[normal],
[normal] you should spend less and therefore have a greater proportion, and I do not think anyone is recommending that in this context. There is
[normal],
[normal] therefore
[normal],
[normal] no standard formula. I absolutely agree that
[normal],
[normal] even if you include local taxes, where 
[normal]Wales
[normal] is today
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]does not allow it any meaningful fiscal accountability. I do not think
[normal],
[normal] in practice
[normal],
[normal] it is going to be possible to get to even the proportions that are conceivable in the case of Scotland, but it should be, in practice, possible, if you include income tax, to get to proportions 
[normal]that
[normal] are at least comparable to those in local government.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Nia[bold] Griffith:[bold] 
[normal]We have seen your submissions that the tax take in 
[normal]Wales
[normal] is considerably lower
[normal], and
[normal] I think you put it at 
[normal]£
[normal]1,300 as opposed to 
[normal]£
[normal]2,000 in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] as a whole. Given as a proportion of the budget of the Welsh Government, would the pain be worth the gain in them putting on 1p extra on that small slice of income tax
[normal],
[normal] which they would have the power to do? In other words, 
[normal]would 
[normal]the amount they could raise really 
[normal]be 
[normal]of any significance in that budget?
[normal]Gerald [bold]Holtham[bold]: 
[normal]The short answer is no. There is a great flaw with this Bill, which stems from the fact t
[normal]hat the British Government take
[normal] the view that 
[normal]Wales
[normal] cannot possibly have anything that 
[normal]they have
[normal] not already given to 
[normal]Scotland
[normal]. 
[normal]We are the runt of the litter: 
[normal]basically, we get the hand
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]me
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]downs that the other people have had and
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]“
[normal]Don
[normal]’
[normal]t, for God
[normal]’
[normal]s s
[normal]ake, ask for anything different.”
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]t was pointed out by the Silk Commission, and 
[normal]indeed by the C
[normal]ommission that I chaired, that this lockstep arrangement
[normal]—
[normal]whereby you have the same tax rates for basic and higher rates and
[normal],
[normal] if you increase the tax
[normal],
[normal] you increase everybody
[normal]’
[normal]s marginal rate
[normal]—
[normal]will make the tax in Wales virtually unusable. As an equalitarian myself
[normal],
[normal] I regret this, but one has to face reality
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]n 
[normal]Wales
[normal],
[normal] you simply cannot afford to r
[normal]aise the top rate of income tax; y
[normal]ou just cannot do it. 
[normal]People move, 
[normal]on average, once every 10 years;
[normal] 50% of the Welsh population lives within 
[normal]25
[normal] miles
[normal] of the border. Anybody on £1 million or £500,000 a year has probably got two homes. You are just going to lose more money than you will gain over a five and 10
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]year period
[normal]. R
[normal]aising the higher rate of tax is impossible in 
[normal]Wales
[normal] unless you wish to lose revenue. Therefore, if you want to raise tax
[normal],
[normal] you have to raise the basic rate only. If you want to cut tax, you can cut the top rate
[normal],
[normal] but these things are ruled out by this legislation. You are making sure that this is a power that is very unlikely to be used.
[normal]Chair:[bold] We must move on; t
[normal]hank you. 
