[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jessica Morden:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you for that. Can I ask Professor Gallagher about the Scottish experience? In terms of the Scotland Act 2012, what are the differences between this and the draft Wales Bill?
[normal]Professor Gallagher[bold]: 
[normal]Very few. The scheme 
[normal]that
[normal] is in this Bill is essentially the same scheme in respect of income tax and small taxes as it is in the Scotland Act 2012. That went through the Scottish Parliament, the Scottish Parliament supported it
[normal],
[normal] and, provided another referendum goes the way in which the UK Government would like it to go, that scheme will come into effect in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] in 2016. 
[normal]W
[normal]e have no experience, as yet, of operating it. 
[normal]I suppose I might add, however, two caveats to what Gerry said. The first is if I might address Ms Griffith
[normal]’
[normal]s question rather more directly. Your question was not about the variability of rates but whether it was worth the pain because you did not raise very much more money. That is a real constraint, but nevertheless there may well come an occasion when a Parliament wants to raise some more money and the tax will allow it to do so. Conversely, in principle, in 
[normal]a 
[normal]Parliament the gearing works the other way in relation to saving money. If you want to cut the taxes, it does not cost you very much pain in reduced services proportionately. So that gearing argument cuts both ways.
