[normal]Q49 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Williams:[bold] 
[normal]Professor Scully, you have very consistently argued the case against the ban on dual candidacy
[normal].
[normal] I recall you both came before the Select Committee at the time
[normal] of 
[normal]the Government of Wales Bill in 2006. You have reiterated your opposition to the ban. Can you remind the Committee why you have taken such a strong stance against the ban?
[normal]Professor Scully[bold]: A
[normal]s I articulated in the written evidence that I submitted, the arguments against dual candidacy are flawed 
[normal]both 
[normal]in principle and have problematic practical implications. I know some people feel very strongly against dual candidacy and I do not challenge the sincerity of their views, but I do believe that they are based on a misunderstanding of the nature of the electoral system that was introduced for Assembly elections. In particular, the argument is made that defeated candidates at the constituency level have b
[normal]een rejected by the electorate and, t
[normal]herefore, they should no
[normal]t be able to enter the Assembly. B
[normal]ut the pr
[normal]oportional variant
[normal] of AMS that we use for Assembly elections that is used in quite a few other countries around the world now is a voting system whereby parties
[normal],
[normal] through the list seats
[normal],
[normal] are compensated if they have been relatively unsuccessful in the constituencies. Parties who have been, in a sense, if you want to put it like that, rej
[normal]ected at the constituency level
[normal] still 
[normal]get some representation in the C
[normal]hamber
[normal],
[normal] and it is difficult to see a strong principled reason why what applies to parties should not also apply to individual candidates. 
[normal]The other reasons why I am opposed to a ban on dual candidacy 
[normal]are
[normal], first, it creates potentially perverse incentives, which I do not think legislation ought to
[normal] do. For instance, if you have 
[normal]separate constituency and list
[normal] 
[normal]groups of candidates
[normal], 
[normal]the list ones then effectively acquire an incentive for their party
[normal]’
[normal]s c
[normal]onstituency candidates to lose—an
[normal]d
[normal],
[normal] indeed
[normal],
[normal] one or two people here know about that directly
[normal]. That is not 
[normal]a sensible sort of incentive to build into a system. Also for the voters, if you particula
[normal]rly favour a list candidate now,
[normal] you maybe would want to vote against that party at the constituency level. 
[normal]But I think there is a third reason 
[normal]that
[normal] is specific to 
[normal]Wales
[normal]. Havi
[normal]ng a very small Assembly of 60 M
[normal]embers, various people, including my colleague here, have argued 
[normal]that 
[normal]that is insufficient. Having such a small body, we need to do everything possible to maximise the quality of the representation within that body
[normal],
[normal] having, in particular, so few people to do the Committee work and all the various roles other than leadership and ministerial. We have a relatively small number of people spread pretty thinly and we need to do everything possible to make sure that those people are of the maximum quality. The 
[normal]New Zealand
[normal] inquiry into this system
[normal] articulated the case very well
[normal] that d
[normal]ual candidacy can help parties not ensure but 
[normal]make more likely the election of the people who those parties believe are their strongest candidates. In 
[normal]Wales
[normal],
[normal] that is something we should be doing.
